{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"da0cec19-682c-4f3c-b7b7-e41d0410db12","content":"## What happened\n\n**Apple's security frameworks don't support DSA.** On macOS, .NET uses Apple's native crypto libraries (Security.framework / CryptoKit), which dropped DSA entirely. In .NET 11, the remaining OpenSSL-based fallback path for `DSA.Create()` on macOS was removed, so the call now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`**.\n\nThis follows a multi-release deprecation arc — `DSA` has carried `[Obsolete]` warnings since .NET 7, and Microsoft has been tightening platform support each release.\n\n## How to fix it\n\n**Option 1 – Use BouncyCastle (recommended for verification-only):**\n\n```csharp\n// dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\nvar signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA1withDSA\");\nsigner.Init(forSigning: false, PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyBytes));\nsigner.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);\nbool valid = signer.VerifySignature(signatureBytes);\n```\n\nThis is pure managed code — no platform crypto dependency.\n\n**Option 2 – Migrate signatures to a modern algorithm** (best long-term):\n\nReplace DSA with **ECDSA** or **Ed25519**. Re-sign artifacts with the new key, then verify with `ECDsa.Create()` which works on all platforms.\n\n**Option 3 – Pin OpenSSL on macOS (fragile, not recommended):**\n\nInstall OpenSSL via Homebrew and use `DSAOpenSsl` directly — but this class is itself obsolete and may be removed in a future release.\n\n## Recommendation\n\nSince you're only *verifying* legacy signatures (not creating new ones), **BouncyCastle** is the lowest-risk fix. Pair it with a migration plan to re-sign with ECDSA so you can drop DSA entirely.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"21be082d-afa9-4b6a-8602-84feb3413140","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS when upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me reason about this from my knowledge.\n\nThis is a known breaking change in .NET. Starting with .NET 7, Microsoft began deprecating older cryptographic algorithms, and DSA specifically has been affected on macOS.\n\nThe key issue: **Apple's CommonCrypto/Security framework dropped DSA support**. .NET on macOS uses Apple's native crypto libraries (via Apple's Security framework / CommonCrypto), and since Apple removed DSA support, .NET cannot provide a DSA implementation on macOS.\n\n\nThe timeline here is that DSA support was removed from .NET on macOS starting in .NET 7, when `DSA.Create()` began throwing `PlatformNotSupportedException`. Since .NET relies on the platform's native cryptographic libraries, and Apple's frameworks no longer support DSA, there's no way for .NET to work around this limitation on macOS. work in .NET 10? On macOS, .NET can fall back to OpenSSL (installed via Homebrew) for cryptographic algorithms that Apple's native framework doesn't support, so DSA might have been available through that path. My best guess is that in .NET 11, either the OpenSSL backend dropped DSA support entirely or the fallback mechanism itself was removed, causing the breaking change.\n\nThe workarounds are to explicitly use the OpenSSL implementation if available, manually parse and verify DSA signatures using ASN.1 tools, switch to a different algorithm altogether since DSA is cryptographically weak, or rely on a third-party library like BouncyCastle. I should give a clear answer about the trajectory of .NET's DSA support and what users can actually do.","outputTokens":1513,"requestId":"2834:18853A:1609FB8:18B213C:6A0285EF"},"id":"5f079236-b419-4d7a-8fcb-6f0a29510fff","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:44:49.870Z","parentId":"6420c1cb-4b62-4061-9af4-2af5047f4423"}
